@node "Main" "OpusFTP.guide"
@next "AddressBook"
  The Directory Opus FTP client - OpusFTP

  OpusFTP is designed to make access to the internet's FTP sites
  withĀDirectory Opus 5 as simple as using your own hard drive.

    @{"Requirements" link "Requirements" 0}
    @{"Installation" link "Installation" 0}
    @{"UsingĀOpusFTP" link "Usage" 0}
    @{"ThisĀDemoĀversion" link "Commercial" 0}
    @{"SupportedĀcommands" link "Commands" 0}
    @{"ArexxĀinterface" link "Arexx" 0}
    @{"ServersĀtested" link "Servers" 0}
    @{"KnownĀbugs" link "Bugs" 0}

    @{"GPĀSoftware" link "GP Software" 0}
@endnode

@node "AddressBook" "AddressBook"
@next "Connect"
@prev "Main"
  The @{b}FTPAddressBook@{ub} command displays a requester which allows you
  toĀ@{"connect" link "Connect" 0} to any FTP site listed in your @{"configurationĀfile" link "Config" 0} simply
  byĀdouble-clicking on the entry or selecting it and clicking the
  OkayĀbutton.
@endnode

@node "Connect" "Connect"
@next "CD"
@prev "AddressBook"
  The @{b}FTPConnect@{ub} command provides requesters for entering the details
  ofĀthe FTP site you wish to connect to.

  You are prompted for the host name of the machine.
  (you may enter the IP number instead if you know it.)

  Next you are prompted for a user name.  This will usually be
  @{b}anonymous@{ub} but you may enter your remote user name if you
  have an account on the remote site.

  If you enter a user name other than anonymous you will be prompted
  for the password of your account.

  * Many anonymous FTP sites have a maximum number of users.
    If you attempt to log in to such a site without using a log
    window you will not see the message which explains this.
    In such cases OpusFTP will display the message "User name
    failed". This error message can also appear if the remote site
    does do not support anonymous logins.
@endnode

@node "CD" "CD"
@next "Copy"
@prev "Connect"
  The @{b}FTPCD@{ub} command allows you to change to a @{"hiddenĀdirectory" link "Hidden Entries" 0}
  byĀproviding a requester.
@endnode

@node "Copy" "Copy"
@next "Rename"
@prev "CD"
  The @{b}FTPCopy@{ub} command allows you to copy @{"hiddenĀfiles" link "Hidden Entries" 0} by providing
  aĀrequester.
@endnode

@node "Rename" "Rename"
@next "Delete"
@prev "Copy"
  The @{b}FTPRename@{ub} command allows you to rename @{"hiddenĀentries" link "Hidden Entries" 0} by
  providingĀa requester.
@endnode

@node "Delete" "Delete"
@next "Command"
@prev "Rename"
  The @{b}FTPDelete@{ub} command allows you to delete @{"hiddenĀentries" link "Hidden Entries" 0} by
  providingĀa requester.
@endnode

@node "Command" "Command"
@next "Set"
@prev "Delete"
  The @{b}FTPCommand@{ub} command lets you send an FTP command directly to
  theĀserver.

  This command is provided mainly for experts who wish to set
  siteĀoptions.

  As an example, you may wish to experiment with FTP commands
  like HELP, STAT, and PWD.

  * CARE: It is possible to confuse OpusFTP when using this command.
    Be careful not to change remote directories or OpusFTP may be
    unable to find the correct remote file paths.

@endnode

@node "Set" "SetVar"
@next "Quit"
@prev "Command"
  The @{b}FTPSetVar@{ub} command lets you set the value of the internal
  OpusFTPĀvariables.

  * Note that this command can be used only with Arexx at present.
    See the provided buttons for examples of use.

  * @{b}LogFile [name]@{ub}
    If name is specified, a new log will be opened using the new
    name.ĀIf a log was already open, it will be closed. If no name is
    specified,Āthe log will be toggled between open/closed using the
    original name inĀthe configuration file:

  FTPSet LogFile "CON:////FTP Log"
  FTPSet LogFile

  * @{b}Debug [n]@{ub}
    If n is provided, the debugging level will be set to this new
    value.ĀIf n is not provided, the debugging level will be toggled
    between 0Āand 1. n must be a decimal integer:

  FTPSet Debug 1
  FTPSet Debug

  * @{b}Timeout n@{ub}
    n must be provided. This sets the maximum number of seconds
    OpusFTPĀwill wait for replies from the server before giving up
    andĀdisconnecting:

  Timeout 60
@endnode

@node "Quit" "Quit"
@next "Config"
@prev "Set"
  The @{b}FTPQuit@{ub} command causes all connected listers to log out as
  soonĀas they can.  It then closes the log if it is open, and allows
  theĀ@{b}ftp.module@{ub} to be removed from memory when neccessary.
@endnode

@node "Config" "Configuration File"
@next "Hidden Entries"
@prev "Quit"
  The Directory Opus FTP Configuration File.

  OpusFTP uses a configuration file in the @{b}DOpus5:FTP@{ub} directory
  calledĀ@{b}ftp.config@{ub} to store its default settings as well as the
  entries forĀyour favourite FTP sites which appear in the
  @{"AddressĀBook" link "AddressBook" 0} requester.

  @{u}Format of the configuration file:@{uu}

  Blank lines and lines beginning with '#' are ignored.

  @{b}@{u}Options:@{ub}@{uu}

  ReadArgs is used to interpret the file using these arguments:

    Log/K,LogOff/S,Debug/K/N,Timeout/K/N

  Each option is a keyword and must be specified to set that option.
  TheĀkeyword and value may be seperated by either a space or an
    '='Ā(equals) sign.
  One or more options may appear on the same line.
  ValuesĀcontaining spaces must be surrounded by double quotes.
  Lines withĀerrors are ignored.
  If an option is specified more than once the lastĀone is used.

  The @{b}Log@{ub} keyword specifies the name of a log window or file
  If the @{b}LogOff@{ub} switch is present, the log will not be opened
    automatically, you can manually open and close the log with the
    @{"SetVarĀLogFile" link "Set" 0} command
  The @{b}Debug@{ub} keyword specifies the level of debugging information to
    print in the log - currently 0 or 1 @{b}
  The Timeout@{ub} keyword specifies the maximum number of seconds to wait
    for responses from the server machine before giving up

  @{u}Examples:@{uu}
    Log "CON:////FTP Log" LogOff Debug 0 Timeout 60

    Log="KCON:////FTP Log/Close/Wait" Debug=1

    Timeout=120

  These values can be changed during operation via the @{"FTPSet" link "Set" 0}
    command.

  @{b}@{u}Address Book Entries:@{ub}@{uu}

  The ReadArgs arguments for an entry are:

  "Anonymous=Anon/S,UserAccount=Acct/S,Alias/K,Host/K,Address=Addr/K
  Ā,User/K,Pass/K,Dir/K"

  An entry MUST contain either the @{b}Anonymous@{ub} or @{b}UserAccount@{ub} switch
  (@{b}Anon@{ub}Āand @{b}Acct@{ub} may be used as abbreviations)

  You may provide a @{b}nickname@{ub} for an FTP site using the
  @{b}Alias@{ub}Ākeyword to specify it - the @{"addressĀbook" link "AddressBook" 0} requester will then
  show theĀalias instead of the real name.

  You MUST specify at least one of the @{b}Host@{ub} or @{b}Address@{ub} options -
  @{b}Host@{ub} is the hostname of the FTP server eg @{b}ftp.commodore.com@{ub}
  @{b}Address@{ub} is the IP address of the server eg @{b}123.456.789.100@{ub} (@{b}Addr@{ub}
  mayĀbe used as an abbreviation)

  For @{b}user accounts@{ub}, the @{b}User@{ub} option specifies your @{b}user name@{ub} on
  theĀhost machine, if this is omitted a requester will appear before
  youĀlog in.

  For @{b}user accounts@{ub} you may specify your @{b}password@{ub} with the
  @{b}Pass@{ub}Ākeyword although it is probably safer to leave it out in which
  case aĀrequester will appear before you log in.

  The @{b}Dir@{ub} option allows you to change to a specific directory
 Āautomatically as soon as you log in.

  @{u}Examples:@{uu}

    Anon Alias=Aminet Host=ftp.somewhere.com Dir=/pub/aminet

    Acct Alias="My account" Addr=100.200.300.400 User=fred Pass=?????
@endnode

@node "Hidden Entries" "Hidden Entries"
@next "Requirements"
@prev "Config"
  Certain circumstances can lead to some files and directories 
  being @{b}hidden@{ub} when using OpusFTP. These are:-

    * If two or more entries have the same spelling but differ in
      case.  This is common on Unix machines where filenames are
      case-sensitive.  An example of this is on Aminet sites where
      there is a @{b}RECENT@{ub} file and a @{b}recent@{ub} directory.
      Because Directory Opus was designed for the Amiga where
      filenames are not case-sensitive, these entries are not
      distinguished and only one will be shown in the lister.

    * If the length of an entry's name is greater than 30 characters 
      it will be truncated. (This is an Opus 5 requirement.)
      The full name will then not be available through the normal
      buttons so the requester must be used.  The requester allows
      you to enter names of up to 80 characters.

    * If you are in a @{b}private@{ub} directory. Many operating
      systems allow files to be stored in directories that cannot be
      listed.  However, if you are given the exact name of the file
      you can still access it.

    * If you are connected to a machine that does not provide
      Unix style directory listing on its FTP software, OpusFTP
      cannot currently understand it - please contact us if you have
      a specific requirement to use such a site.

    * If you abort while listing a directory.  This can be very
      useful on machines with slow connections or large
      directories if you know your way around.
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"
@next "Installation"
@prev "Hidden Entries"
OpusFTP requires the following:

    AmigaDOS version 2.0 or higher
    Directory Opus 5.1 or higher
    @{"AmiTCP/IP" link "AmiTCP" 0} version 4.0 or higher - shareware or commercial version

    @{"MLink" link "MLink" 0} may be used instead of @{"AmiTCP" link "AmiTCP" 0} but has not been tested
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"
@next "Commands"
@prev "Requirements"
  To install OpusFTP on your hard drive use the installer provided.

  If you wish to install manually:-

    Create a directory in your DOpus5: assign called FTP
    Copy the ftp.config into this directory
    Copy ftp.module into DOpus5:Modules/
    Copy the Buttons directory to DOpus5:Buttons/
    Copy the Images directory to DOpus5:Images/

  If you are running Opus 5 when you install OPusFTP, you will have
  to quit Opus and re-run it for it to recognise the new FTPĀmodule.
@endnode

@node "Commands" "Commands"
@next "Arexx"
@prev "Installation"
  OpusFTP supports the following built-in Opus commands:-

  @{b}These commands are supported directly with some differences:@{ub}

    Copy            Delete
    MakeDir         Parent
    Rename          Root

    Copy will copy file only, it will not copy directories.
    Copying an existing file where the new file is larger than the
    old provides a @{"resume" link "Resume" 0} feature.
    Delete will delete directories only if they are empty. (But
    this does depend on the server's operating system.)
    Rename does not allow wildcards.

  @{b}These commands are supported by first downloading the selected
  files intoĀthe T: directory:@{ub}

    AnsiRead        DoubleClick
    HexRead         Play
    Print           Read
    Run             Show
    SmartRead

  @{b}These extra commands are provided by OpusFTP:@{ub}

    @{"FTPAddressBook" link "AddressBook" 0}  @{"FTPConnect" link "Connect" 0}
    @{"FTPCD" link "CD" 0}           @{"FTPCopy" link "Copy" 0}
    @{"FTPRename" link "Rename" 0}       @{"FTPDelete" link "Delete" 0}
    @{"FTPCommand" link "Command" 0}      @{"FTPSetVar" link "Set" 0}
    @{"FTPQuit" link "Quit" 0}

  Opus does not currently allow arguments to be passed to external
  modules.  If you wish to pass arguments to these commands you must
  use the @{"Arexx" link "Arexx" 0} equivalents.
@endnode

@node "Arexx" "Arexx"
@next "AmiTCP"
@prev "Commands"
  OpusFTP has a (currently limited) Arexx port.

  The Arexx port name is OPUSFTP.

  Arexx commands are available in OpusFTP include:-

    @{"AddressBook" link "AddressBook" 0}
    @{"Connect" link "Connect" 0} [host] [user] [password] [directory]
    @{"CD" link "CD" 0} handle
    @{"Copy" link "Copy" 0} handle
    @{"Rename" link "Rename" 0} handle
    @{"Delete" link "Delete" 0} handle
    @{"Command" link "Command" 0} handle [ftp command]
    @{"SetVar" link "Set" 0} variable value

  The Arexx commands are named after the equivalent built-in commands
  but do not have the preceeding @{b}FTP@{ub} as part of the name.

  The Arexx commands are designed primarily for use in Opus buttons
  butĀmay be fully supported in a future version of OPusFTP.
@endnode

@node "AmiTCP" "AmiTCP"
@next "MLink"
@prev "Arexx"
  AmiTCP/IP is the most videly used TCP/IP protocol stack for the
  Amiga. AmiTCP/IP utilizes the standard Sana-II network device
  drivers and provides an application level socket interface to the
  Internet protocol suite as an Amiga shared library.

  AmiTCP is available from Aminet in the comm/tcp directory.

  AmiTCP/IP is a product of Network Solutions Development Inc.

