@node "MLink" "MLink"
@next "Resume"
@prev "AmiTCP"
  Multilink (or Mlink) is a package which simulates a direct
  connection to the internet.  If you have an account on a UNIX
  machineĀconnected to the internet, you can run Multilink on the
  UNIX machineĀand your Amiga, and Multilink will allow you to use
  all thoseĀwonderful Amiga networking applications such as
  Grapevine, DaFTP,Ātelnet and Amosaic without having to have a real
  SLIP or PPPĀconnection.

  Multilink requires at least AmigaDOS 2.1 and an account on a
  UNIXĀhost connected to the internet.

  Multilink is available from Aminet in the comm/net directory
@endnode

@node "Resume" "Resume"
@next "Usage"
@prev "MLink"
  OpusFTP includes a handy @{b}Resume@{ub} feature which can be useful if
  youĀhave a slow or unreliable connection, or have to disconnect in
  theĀmiddle of a transfer, or even if you suffer a crash!

  To continue a file transfer, simply re-establish the connection,
  locate the same file and resume the transfer.  Select the
 Āfile you wish to resume, make sure the original partial file is in
  theĀdestination lister and click the Copy button. A requester will
  appearĀgiving you several options.  You may skip or replace the
  whole file asĀusual in Opus, or click on Resume to get (or put)
  the rest of theĀfile from where you left off.

  This requester automatically appears whenever you attempt to copy
  aĀfile to or from a normal Opus directory when a file with an
  identicalĀname already exists and the source file is larger than
  the destinationĀfile.

  * Not all FTP servers may support this operation.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Using OpusFTP"
@next "Servers"
@prev "Resume"
  To use OpusFTP you must have AmiTCP set up and running first.
  OfĀcourse if you want to access the internet you must also be
  connectedĀto your slip or PPP (or whatever you have access to)
  provider viaĀmodem etc.

  Once you are familiar with the internet and FTP you should setĀup
  your @{"addressĀbook" link "AddressBook" 0} by editing the @{"configurationĀfile" link "Config" 0}.

  To operate OpusFTP, load the FTP buttons provided and click on the 
  @{"AddressĀBook" link "AddressBook" 0} button or the @{"Connect" link "Connect" 0} button.


  Once you have a successful connection, you may copy files in the
  usual manner as if they were local files by using the Lister
  Buttons, Button Banks or other Opus techniques such as
  drag-and-drop.

  On many sites you may see entries such as:-

    -> Aminet

  This is a Unix symbolic link which may point to a file or a
    directory.
  The full path of the real entry will be shown in the comment
    field.

  Usually it is possible to guess whether a link is to a file or
    directory but this may not always be the case so it is possible
    for them to appear in the wrong colour in the lister.
  The '->' symbol is provided so you can distinguish them in this
    case and is not part of the filename.
  On some systems it is not possible to determine the true size of
    a symbolic link so there will be no progress bar when downloading
    these files.
@endnode

@node "Servers" "Servers tested"
@next "Bugs"
@prev "Usage"
  OpusFTP has been extensively tested on many FTP servers.
  OpusFTP expects remote servers to provide directories in standard 
  Unix format.

  These following servers are known to function correctly:-
    Unix (all flavours)
    Amiga
    News-OS
    PC's running Novell NetWare
    NeXT
    Windows NT
    Macintosh
    Some OS/2 servers

  These servers do not:-
    VAX/VMS
    VM/CMS
    Some OS/2 servers

  If you are running an FTP daemon on an Amiga and wish to connect to
  it with OpusFTP, make sure that you have a Unix style @{b}ls@{ub} command
  installed to produce the correct output.

  If you are having trouble with a particular server
  please contact @{"GPĀSoftware" link "GP Software" 0} with details.
@endnode

@node "Bugs" "Known bugs"
@next "GP Software"
@prev "Servers"
  Known bugs in OpusFTP:

  .  Timestamps are often incorrect for copied or created entries.
  .  DOpus's internal directory caches cannot be used for FTP
     directories.
  .  Other custom lister handlers (eg LhaDir) may not be compatible
     with OpusFTP.
  .  Vax/VMS, VM/CMS, and some OS/2 FTP servers do not work with
     OpusFTP.
  .  OpusFTP does not work reliably if more than one copy of
     Directory Opus is running.
  .  You must quit OpusFTP manually at present - even if you quit
     Directory Opus itself.
@endnode

